04616nam a22006495i 9780271088402DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20212020pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710884027 a10.1515/97802710884022doi  a(DE-B1597)584232  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aPN56.D6 7aLIT0240002bisacsh04a809/.9336297722231 aKendall-Morwick, Karalyn, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCanis Modernis :bHuman/Dog Coevolution in Modernist Literature /cKaralyn Kendall-Morwick. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2020  a1 online resource (216 p.) :b2 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAnimalibus: Of Animals and Cultures ;v1900tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Modernism and the Canine Condition -- t1 Canine Origins: Jack London and Konrad Lorenz -- t2 Mongrelizing Form: Virginia Woolf 's Flush -- t3 The New Dog: Albert Payson Terhune and J. R. Ackerley -- t4 Dogging the Subject: Samuel Beckett and Emmanuel Levinas -- tCoda: Modernism and Literary Canine Studies -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aModernist literature might well be accused of going to the dogs. From the strays wandering the streets of Dublin in James Joyce's Ulysses to the highbred canine subject of Virginia Woolf's Flush, dogs populate a range of modernist texts. In many ways, the dog in the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries became a potent symbol of the modern condition-facing, like the human species, the problem of adapting to modernizing forces that relentlessly outpaced it. Yet the dog in literary modernism does not function as a stand-in for the human. In this book, Karalyn Kendall-Morwick examines the human-dog relationship in modernist works by Virginia Woolf, Jack London, Albert Payson Terhune, J. R. Ackerley, and Samuel Beckett, among others. Drawing from the evolutionary theories of Charles Darwin and the scientific, literary, and philosophical work of Donna Haraway, Temple Grandin, and Carrie Rohman, she makes a case for the dog as a coevolutionary and coadapting partner of humans. As our coevolutionary partners, dogs destabilize the human: not the autonomous, self-transparent subject of Western humanism, the human is instead contingent, shaped by its material interactions with other species. By demonstrating how modernist representations of dogs ultimately mongrelize the human, this book reveals dogs' status both as instigators of the crisis of the modern subject and as partners uniquely positioned to help humans adapt to the turbulent forces of modernization.Accessibly written and convincingly argued, this study shows how dogs challenge the autonomy of the human subject and the humanistic underpinnings of traditional literary forms. It will find favor with students and scholars of modernist literature and animal studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aDogs in literature. 0aHuman-animal relationships in literature. 0aModernism (Literature). 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Modern / General .2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311074521440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271088402zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271088402423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271088402.jpg  a978-3-11-074521-4  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK